<TITLE> Sri Lanka bus blast kills 16, wounds 40 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 COLOMBO, April 25 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - At least 16 people were killed and 40 wounded when a bomb ripped through a packed commuter bus on the outskirts of the Sri Lankan capital on Friday, police said. "Sixteen people killed and about 40 injured from the explosion," police spokesman N.K. Ilangakoon said. W. Gunawardena, a doctor at the Colombo South Teaching Hospital said 12 bodies had been admitted, including a child. The blast, which occurred in a residential suburb during the evening rush hour, comes days after dozens of Tamil Tiger fighters and government troops were killed in heavy fighting on the Jaffna Peninsula in the far north of the island. Fighting between government forces and the Tigers has intensified since the government formally pulled out of a six-year-old ceasefire pact in January. The rebels, who want an independent state in the north and east, have hit back with bombings in Colombo and elsewhere in the relatively peaceful south when they have come under military pressure in the past
